feat_req__abi_compatible_data_types__prv.content:
An ABI-compatible ``AbiVec<T, N>`` type shall be provided in both C++ and Rust with the specified layout.

.. code-block:: rust

   #[repr(C)]
   pub struct AbiVec<T> {
      len: u32,
      capacity: u32,
      elements: [T; N],
   }

.. code-block:: cpp

   template<typename T, std::size_t N>
   struct AbiVec {
   private:
      std::uint32_t len;
      std::uint32_t capacity;
      T elements[N];
   };

An ABI-compatible ``AbiResult<T, E>`` type shall be provided in both C++ and Rust with the specified layout.

.. code-block:: rust

   #[repr(C)]
   pub struct AbiResult<T, E> {
      is_ok: u8,
      value: AbiResultUnion<T, E>,
   }

   #[repr(C)]
   union AbiResultUnion<T, E> {
      ok: T,
      err: E,
   }

.. code-block:: cpp

   template<typename T, typename E>
   struct AbiResult {
   private:
      std::uint8_t is_ok;
      union {
         T ok;
         E err;
      } value;
   };

gd_req__verification_link_tests_cpp.content:
For linking C++ test suites to requirements **record properties** shall be used. Attributes
which are common for all test cases can be specified in the Setup Function (SetUp()), the other
attributes which are specific for each test case need to be specified within the test case:

.. code-block:: cpp

  class TestSuite : public ::testing::Test{
     public:
        void SetUp() override
        {
           RecordProperty("TestType", "<TestType>");
           RecordProperty("DerivationTechnique", "<DerivationTechnique>");
           ...
        }
  };

  TEST_F(TestSuite, <Test Case>)
  {
     RecordProperty("PartiallyVerifies", "ID_2, ID_3, ...");
     RecordProperty("FullyVerifies", "ID_4, ID_5, ...");
     RecordProperty("Description", "<Description>");

     ASSERT ...
  }

